{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500687","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500687"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:16:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:16:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1660"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1660","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1660"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.25,0.35,0.2,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1660"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43468"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1660","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1660"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1660"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28453"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4626"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1217"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1237"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2731"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6078"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35666"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43468","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43468"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 82-year-old woman presented to the Emergency Department with a 36 hour history of sudden onset left-sided arm and leg weakness, slurred speech and left-sided facial droop. She has a medical history of:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHypertension (well controlled with perindopril)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProvoked DVT 5 years ago (treated with enoxaparin)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt follow up 6 weeks post diagnosis, her GP noted a mild haemoglobin drop and platelet count drop from 380 x10\u003Csup\u003E^\u003C/sup\u003E9/L to 130 x10\u003Csup\u003E^\u003C/sup\u003E9/L (150-450) as recorded in her previous blood tests\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsthma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA plain CT brain scan does not demonstrate any evidence of intracranial haemorrhage. Her eGFR is \u0026gt;90ml/kg/hr. Her weight is 78kg. She is admitted to the Stroke Unit for ongoing further management.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"For her current admission, which one of the following is the most appropriate choice of VTE prophylaxis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Unfractionated heparin 5000 units subcut twice daily","Rivaroxaban 10 mg oral once daily","Enoxaparin 40 mg subcut once daily","Fondaparinux 2.5 mg subcut once daily","Warfarin 5 mg oral once daily"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has had an acute stroke and is likely to have limited mobility as an inpatient for a number of days. Furthermore, her history of provoked DVT puts her at higher risk of another venous thromboembolism. Thus, she requires VTE prophylaxis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the stem, her previous treatment with enoxaparin resulted in thrombocytopenia acutely, which is highly suspicious for Heparin Induced Thrombotic Thrombocytopaenia Syndrome (HITTS).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore, VTE prophylaxis with \u003Cstrong\u003Eenoxaparin\u003C/strong\u003E is unsuitable as she may develop HITTS again. Using unfractionated heparin for VTE prophylaxis is also unsuitable as this can also cause HITTS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFondaparinux\u003C/strong\u003E is an anticoagulant which, like heparin, catalyses the activity of antithrombin to inhibit Factor Xa and is administered subcutaneously. The heparin:PF4 complex is the antigen in heparin-induced thrombocytopenia (HIT) but Fondaparinux has no affinity for Platelet Factor 4 (PF4) and therefore is safe to use in patients with a current episode or past history of HITTS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWarfarin\u003C/strong\u003E is an anticoagulant that is NOT used for VTE prophylaxis. It can be used for anticoagulation to treat established DVTs/PEs, and can also be used for anticoagulation to reduce stroke risk in patients with atrial fibrillation (particularly if they have a mechanical heart valve).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERivaroxaban\u003C/strong\u003E is an anticoagulant that is usually used in the treatment of established DVTs/PEs, and can also be used for anticoagulation to reduce stroke risk in patients with atrial fibrillation. Occasionally it is used in VTE prophylaxis for patients post orthopaedic procedure (it has only been evaluated for use in VTE prophylaxis after elective total hip or total knee replacement surgery) (3).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The recommended anticoagulant in patients with HITTS is fondaparinux or danaparoid."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Venous thromboembolism: prophylaxis. Victoria: eTG; 2018 March [cited 2021 January 22]. Available from: https://tgldcdp-tg-org-au.proxy.library.adelaide.edu.au/viewTopic?topicfile=venous-thromboembolism-prevention\u0026guidelineName=Cardiovascular#toc_d1e149.","Ibbotson T, Perry CM. Danaparoid: a review of its use in thromboembolic and coagulation disorders. Drugs. 2002; 62(15): 2283-314.","NPS Medicinewise. Rivaroxaban (Xarelto) for preventing venous thromboembolism after hip or knee replacement surgery. https://www.nps.org.au/radar/articles/rivaroxaban-xarelto-for-preventing-venous-thromboembolism-after-hip-or-knee-replacement-surgery"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28453"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1660"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28453"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-03-18T18:26:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-12T08:08:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1660"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43468"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"upda